text: For folks at medium-to-large organizations where doing it manually for every employee isn't an option. I'm talking about things like IAM for K8s/Nomad, Postgres/MySQL/Mongo, SSH, etc - not necessarily just getting access to those resources in AWS/GCP/Azure, but actually configuring permissions for new hires (and ensuring those permissions are cleared when they leave!).

Show HN: I created a site to help HN users give the perfect Christmas gift
text:
The idea of creating this site came to me when I was thinking of gifts to get family and friends for Christmas after a very exhausting work week.

Getting Christmas gifts or gifts in general can be time consuming and mind draining if you are the type of person that likes to give thoughtful gifts and does not like to repeat gifts.

I decided to compile data of key points like gender, age group, hobbies, favorite things, favorite sports etc of the person receiving the gift, so as to suggest several gifts the receiver is most likely to love.

Since I wanted to share this with others that might need the help and I had little time (since its already 4 weeks to Christmas) to start creating a website from scratch, decided to just create a blog for it. I will set aside time to create a website to help users with tailored gifts(I'll have to do some crowd sourcing to get more data & key points so as to give the best gift suggestions).

Check it out, I hope it helps you give the perfect Christmas gift this year and send feedbacks my way.

Ask HN: Why aren't tweets picked up by the duplicate filter?
text:
I'm not sure Elon Musk shitposts constitute news at any time, but why are people able to post the same tweet over and over without being flagged by HN's otherwise-efficient duplicate filter? HN strips query data from URLs before they are posted, maybe it should do so prior to the duplicate check too since most Twitter URLs come with a large helping of cruft.

And please, check the New page before submitting. There are 4 links to the same evidence-free tweet in the last 10 minutes.

Ask HN: Do you know any good paid newsletters?
text:
Do you have any links to share for quality fee-based newsletters?

- No advertisements.

- Any subject, language or country can be interesting.

- Paper, email or RSS based.

- Written. No video or audio podcasts.

- Not too much editorialism or buzz, just information.

I have almost completely abandoned the sponsored newspaper press, which only transcribes the ambient psychosis and the big media agencies.

I'm looking for new sources, there's a lot of good stuff in blogs, specialized press and podcasts, but I've recently seen some old-fashioned paid newsletters in the field of economics and I find the model interesting but not widespread outside of economics and societal circles.
